06805nam a22009255i 9783110773651DE-B159720230502090707.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230502t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107736517 a10.1515/97831107736512doi  a(DE-B1597)612614  a(OCoLC)1322125908  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aConnected Stories :bContacts, Traditions and Transmissions in Premodern Mediterranean Islam /ced. by Mohamed Meouak, Cristina Puente. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (X, 312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in the History and Culture of the Middle East ,x2198-0853 ;v4400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of contributors -- tConnected Stories. Introduction -- tPart I: Linguistic Stories -- tSociolinguistic Infrastructures -- tWays of Knowledge -- tPart II: Intellectual Stories -- tLe mālikisme irakien et le Maghreb -- tIbn ʿAbd Rabbihi: Adab and the Rational Sciences -- tPart III: Material Stories -- tSacred Cubes within Sacred Spheres -- tQuelques remarques sur la diffusion du minaret-escalier et son lien avec les ibadites -- tPart IV: Spiritual Stories -- tAn Unpublished Arabic Text on the Martyrdom of the Christians of Najrān’ -- tIbn Saʿdūn al-Qayrawānī (m. 485/1092), un transmetteur de connaissances juridiques, mystiques et historiques en Occident musulman -- tFrom Fez to Mecca, from Mecca to Fez -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConcepts such as influence, imitation, emulation, transmission or plagiarism are transcendental to cultural history and the subject of universal debate. They are not mere labels imposed by modern historiography on ancient texts, nor are they the result of a later interpretation of ways of transmitting and teaching, but are concepts defined and discussed internally, within all cultures, since time immemorial, which have yielded very diverse results. In the case of culture, or better Arab-Islamic cultures, we could analyze and discuss endlessly numerous terms that refer to concepts related to the multiple ways of perceiving the Other, receiving his knowledge and producing new knowledge. The purpose of this book evolves around these concepts, and it aims to become part of a very long tradition of studies on this subject that is essential to the understanding of the processes of reception and creation. The authors analyze them in depth through the use of examples that are based on the well-known idea that societies in different regions did not remain isolated and indifferent to the literary, religious or scientific creations that were developed in other territories and moreover that the flow of ideas did not always occur in only one direction. Contacts, both voluntary and involuntary, are never incidental or marginal, but are rather the true engine of the evolution of knowledge and creation. It can also be stated that it has been the awareness of the existence of multidimensional cultural relations which has allowed modern historiography on Arab cultures to evolve and be enriched in recent decades.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023)  aArabic-Islamic World.  aCultural History.  aKnowledge History.  aMiddle Ages.1 aAmara, Allaoua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenhima, Yassir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoloix-Gallardo, Bárbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEchevarría, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForcada, Miquel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKönig, Daniel G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary